In [[film theory]], the term '''oneiric''' ({{IPAc-en|oʊ|ˈ|n|aɪ|r|ɪ|k}}; "pertaining to [[dream]]s") refers to the depiction of dream-like states or to the use of the metaphor of a dream or the dream-state in the analysis of a film.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bacher|first1=Hans P|title=Film Analysis|journal=Dream Worlds|date=1 January 2008|pages=12–27|doi=10.1016/b978-0-240-52093-3.50005-7|url=https://doi.org/10.1016/b978-0-240-52093-3.50005-7|publisher=Focal Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sparshott|first1=F.E.|title=Vision and Dream in the Cinema|journal=Philosophic Exchange: Annual Proceedings|date=1971|volume=1|page=116|url=http://digitalcommons.brockport.edu/phil_ex/vol2/iss1/13/}}</ref><ref name=eber/>{{rp|3-4}}
==History== Early film theorists such as [[Ricciotto Canudo]] (1879–1923) and [[Jean Epstein]] (1897–1953) argued that films had a dreamlike quality. [[Raymond Bellour]] and [[Guy Rosolato]] have made psychoanalytical analogies between films and the dream state, claiming films as having a "latent" content that can be [[psychoanalysis|psychoanalyzed]] as if it were a dream. {{ill|Lydia Marinelli|de}} states that before the 1930s, psychoanalysts "primarily attempted to apply the interpretative schemata found in [[Sigmund Freud]]'s ''[[Interpretation of Dreams]]'' to films."{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}
Author Douglas Fowler surmises that "images arising from dreams are the well spring of all our efforts to give enduring form and meaning to the urgencies within," seeing this as the reason why "the deep structure of human narrative is conceived in dreams and the genesis of all myth is dreams."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fowler|first1=Douglas|title=The Kingdom of Dreams in Literature and Film: Selected Papers from the Tenth Annual Florida State University Conference on Literature and Film|date=1986|publisher=University Presses of Florida|location=Tallahassee|isbn=0813008638|page=10}}</ref> Author Robert Eberwein describes the filmic experience as the merging of a viewer's consciousness with the projected consciousness of the screen's subject, a process whereby the viewer's prior experiences with dreaming "help to create a sense of oneness" with cinema, causing the gap between viewer and what is being viewed to narrow.<ref name=eber>{{cite book|last1=Eberwein|first1=Robert T.|title=Film & the Dream Screen: A Sleep and a Forgetting|date=1984|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton, N.J.|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/book/33536|isbn=0691066191}}</ref>{{rp|53}} Under this theory, no matter what is being shown on the screen — whether the literal representation of a character dreaming, or the fictional characters of a story going on about their fictional lives — the very process of viewing film itself "replicates activities associated with the oneiric experience."<ref name=eber/>{{rp|81-82}}
Films and dreams are also connected in psychological analysis by examining the relationship between the cinema screening process and the spectator (who is perceived as passive). [[Roland Barthes]], a French literary critic and [[Semiotics|semiotician]], described film spectators as being in a "para-oneiric" state, feeling "sleepy and drowsy as if they had just woken up" when a film ends. Similarly, the French [[Surrealism|surrealist]] [[André Breton]] argues that film viewers enter a state between being "awake and falling asleep", what French filmmaker [[René Clair]] called a "dreamlike state". [[Edgar Morin]]'s ''Le cinéma ou l'homme imaginaire'' (1956) and [[Jean Mitry]]'s first volume of ''Esthétique et psychologie du cinéma'' (1963) also discuss the connection between films and the dream state.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}
==Filmmakers== Filmmakers described as using oneiric or dreamlike elements in their films include [[Sergei Parajanov]] (e.g., ''[[Shadows of Forgotten Ancestors]]''), [[David Lynch]] (e.g., ''[[Twin Peaks]]'', ''[[Mulholland Drive (film)|Mulholland Drive]]''),<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lentzner|first1=Jay R.|last2=Ross|first2=Donald R.|title=The Dreams That Blister Sleep: Latent Content and Cinematic Form in Mulholland Drive|journal=American Imago|date=26 April 2005|volume=62|issue=1|pages=120|doi=10.1353/aim.2005.0016|url=https://doi.org/10.1353/aim.2005.0016|issn=1085-7931}}</ref> [[Andrei Tarkovsky]] (e.g. ''[[Andrei Rublev (film)|Andrei Rublev]]'' and ''[[Solaris (1972 film)|Solaris]]''),<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Petric|first1=Vlada|title=Tarkovsky's Dream Imagery|journal=Film Quarterly|date=December 1989|volume=43|issue=2|pages=28–34|doi=10.1525/fq.1989.43.2.04a00040|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1525/fq.1989.43.2.04a00040}}</ref> [[Stan Brakhage]] (e.g., ''[[Dog Star Man]]''), [[Michelangelo Antonioni]] (e.g. ''[[The Passenger (1975 film)|The Passenger]]''), [[Jaromil Jireš]] (e.g., ''[[Valerie and Her Week of Wonders (film)|Valerie and Her Week of Wonders]]''), [[Krzysztof Kieslowski]] (e.g. ''[[The Double Life of Veronique]]''),<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Santilli|first1=Paul C.|title=Cinema and Subjectivity in Krzysztof Kieslowski|journal=Journal of Aesthetics and Art Criticism|date=December 2006|volume=64|issue=1|pages=147–156|doi=10.1111/j.0021-8529.2006.00236.x|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.0021-8529.2006.00236.x}}</ref> [[Federico Fellini]] (e.g., ''[[Amarcord]]''), [[Ingmar Bergman]] (e.g., ''[[Wild Strawberries (film)|Wild Strawberries]]''), [[Jean Cocteau]] (e.g., ''[[Orphic Trilogy]]''), [[Raúl Ruiz (director)|Raúl Ruiz]] (e.g., ''[[City of Pirates]]''), [[Edgar G. Ulmer]] (e.g., ''[[The Black Cat (1934 film)|The Black Cat]]''), [[Jacques Tourneur]] (e.g., ''[[I Walked With a Zombie]]''), [[Maya Deren]],<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Nichols|editor1-first=Bill|title=Maya Deren and the American Avant-Garde|date=2001|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520227323|url=http://www.ucpress.edu/book.php?isbn=9780520227323}}</ref> [[Wojciech Has]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Toepplitz|first1=Krzysztof-Teodor|title=The Films of Wojciech Has|journal=Film Quarterly|date=December 1964|volume=18|issue=2|pages=2–6|doi=10.2307/1210931|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.2307/1210931}}</ref> and [[Kenneth Anger]].<!--Before making an addition, please cite a reliable source that specifically uses the term, and not based on your own personal opinion.-->
