{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = The Strange Case of Mrs. Hudson's Cat: And Other Science Mysteries Solved by Sherlock Holmes | title_orig = | translator = | image = The Strange Case of Mrs. Hudson's Cat.jpg| caption = | author = [[Colin Bruce]] | cover_artist = | country = | language = [[English language|English]] | series = | genre = [[Short stories]] | publisher = [[Addison–Wesley]] | release_date = 1997 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]] | pages = | isbn = 0-201-46139-0 | isbn_note = (first edition, hardback) | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''The Strange Case of Mrs. Hudson's Cat: And Other Science Mysteries Solved by Sherlock Holmes''''' is a collection of [[Sherlock Holmes pastiches|Sherlock Holmes pastiche]] stories by [[Colin Bruce]] which attempts to teach scientific concepts via Holmesian mysteries.<ref name="nyt">[https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/10/05/bib/971005.rv102432.html ''The Strange Case of Mrs. Hudson's Cat: And Other Science Mysteries Solved by Sherlock Holmes''] review at [[The New York Times]]</ref> With Watson's assistance, Holmes solves cases involving elastic space-time and quantum theory.<ref>[https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/5.06/beta.html On Newsstands Now] at [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]</ref> It has also been published as '''''The Einstein Paradox'''''.
[[Professor Challenger]] also appears in some of the stories.
A further book, ''Conned Again, Watson! Cautionary Tales of Logic, Math, and Probability'', which is more mathematically oriented, was published in 2001.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/conned-again-watson-cautionary-tales-of-logic-math-and-probability/oclc/45803637 ''Conned Again, Watson!''] at [[WorldCat]]</ref>
